The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 BCCI extends pension cover

Mumbai: Cricketers of yesteryear will benefit from the Board of Control for Cricket in Indias largesse, which decided to extend its pension scheme on a mega scale here on Sunday. 

The likes of Sunil Gavaskar and Mohinder Amarnath, part of the 1983 World Cup-winning team, will receive up to Rs 35,000 as monthly pension, it was decided by the BCCI working committee, which met here on Sunday. 

The committee decided to extend the existing pension scheme, which covered those who played before 1975, to include those who represented India in Tests and one-day Internationals till December 31, 1993. 

Accordingly, those who have played in 25 Tests or more would be eligible for Rs 35,000 each, while those who played in less than 25 Tests would be eligible for Rs 25,000. 

Besides, umpires who stood in more than 25 Tests or one-dayers would receive a pension of Rs 10,000 each. 

Pawar said the Cricket Association of Bengal (CAB) had withdrawn a letter given to the BCCI on the TV rights tender issue. 

The CAB representative (Chitrak Mitra) agreed to withdraw the letter after hearing our explanations, Pawar said after the meeting. 

Meanwhile, the BCCI has agreed to pay around $200,000 to the ICC for increasing the staging centres of this years Champions Trophy from three to four. 

Ahmedabad is gearing up to host five ODIs for the Champions Trophy in October-November, Gujarat Cricket Association (GCA) officials said here on Sunday, adds another report. 

Rajeev Shukla, meanwhile, was on Sunday appointed as manager of the Indian squad for the ODIs in Abu Dhabi. (PTI) 




